<head> <title>ANARCHY</title>

</head><body bgcolor="#000000" text="#ffffff" link="#00cc00" vlink="#ffff00" alink="#00ff00">

<img src=anarchy.jpg>
<center><font size="10"><B>ANARCHY RULES</b></font></center><BR>
<a href="http://www.anarchy-unlimited.com" border="0"><IMG SRC="bloody.gif"></A>
<br><img src="monk.gif"><br>

<FONT SIZE="5">Anarchy Unlimited is a consortium of young miscreants out to reap the profits of their own dementia.</FONT>

<h1>Links:</h1>
<a href="http://www.anarchy-unlimited.com">Anarchy Unlimited</A><br>

<img src="monk.gif">
<br><br>


<h2>You are interested in my views about anarchy?<br>
</h2>
Fine. <br>
As you might already have guessed, I suppose anarchy to be a real alternative
to any existing society.<br>
On this page I'll try to show why I think, anarchy could be possible. 
Furthermore I want to collect many facts about anarchy, its history and its
protagonists. <p>
<b><i>During the next weeks this page will change as often as I've got the time
 for it, so make sure to add it to your bookmarks and visit soon again :)</i><br>
Ah, last but not least: I know my english is not as perfect as it could be.
If you find some really messy phrases, 
<a href="mailto:jim@mail.commonlink.com">please let me know</a>.
</b>
 
<h2>What <i>is</i> anarchy?</h2>

Often the words "anarchy" and "chaos" are used as equivalents. <br>
This is complete bullshit. Could you imagine a society based on <i>chaos</i>? <br>
Well, I think also no anarchist (btw: I wouldn't call me an anarchist) could.<br>
For this fact I found the sentence 
"Anarchy is not chaos - but order without control."<p>

"Anarchy" comes from the greek word "archia" (hmm, how to write that down,
without greek letters? 
Any <a href="mailto:jim@mail.commonlink.com">suggestions</a>?)  
what means "power, control", and the prefix "an" just means "without".<p>

Now here's Webster's Definition for "anarchy":<br>
an.ar.chy \'an-*r-ke-\ n [ML anarchia, fr. Gk, fr.anarchos rulerless,
 fr. an- + ar]chos ruler - more at ARCH- <br>
<ul>
<li>
1a: absence of government 
</li>
<li>
1b: a state of lawlessness or political
disorder due to the absence of governmental authority 
</li>
<li>
1c: a utopian society having no government and made up of individuals
who enjoy complete freedom 
</li>
<li>
2: absence or denial of authority or order : DISORDER 
</li>
</ul>
For that, <i>anarchy</i> in its original meaning describes a state where nobody 
rules anybody, just as 1c in Webster's said. 

<h2><i>How</i> is anarchy?</h2>

Is this idea, "nobody rules anybody", so far away from <i>democracy</i>?<br>
O.K., in democratic systems we <i>do have</i> control but the ones who rule 
the other ones are elected, so this is a progress compared to former systems
like absolutism or despotism.<p>

If democracy is a progress compared to, let's say, absolutism, could you
imagine anarchy to be a progress compared to democracy?
No? Maybe you have problems with people killing other ones in the name of
anarchy and calling themselves anarchists.<p>

If you look close to the <i>meaning</i> of the word as described above, you
could come to this conclusion: people who kill others DO have power over them,
furthermore they use (or better: <i>abuse</i>) this power. 
Thus it's impossible to call them anarchists.<p>

